I reviewed Mr. Matthew's UI claim to be sure that we had correctly
applied UI law.  The original Adjudicator's decision was that he
admitted staying on the job for 6 years when he conditions were the same
from the date of hire.  UI laws do not allow payment of benefits when an
individuals puts up with adverse conditions for that long and then quits
because of those conditions.  Mr. Matthews appealed that decision and,
during the appeals hearing, two witnesses testified that the manager had
always cursed at Mr. Matthews and most other employees.  This testimony
served to enforce the ruling of the Adjudicator.  The Appeals Referee
affirmed the Adjudicator's decision and then Mr. Matthew's appealed to
the Commission.  The attorney representing the Commission affirmed all
prior decisions.  As of this date, Mr. Matthews as not informed us of
any further appeals and his appeal rights have expired.

I telephoned Mr. Matthews saying that I wanted to see if he had any
questions about the way his UI claim had been handled and about the way
the UI law had been administered.  When I explained that  the ruling
from the Adjudicator was based upon the fact that he waited for six
years to quit, he seemed to see everything in a new light.  I think he
wanted someone to understand that he shouldn't have had to take the
"abuse;" he just took it too long.  Although he still wasn't happy to
not be receiving UI benefits, he was pleased to have been contacted and
was glad to finally understand the process and the decision.
Additionally, I suggested several other state agencies that might be of
help to him.  When he kept wanting some way to tell someone about how
his employer acted, I referred him to the Dept. of Labor to file a
complaint.  Mr. Matthews did tell me that he was approved for Food
Stamps this morning.

