Dear Mr. Canady,

Until late November, I had worked for 32 years continuously, contributing to the unemployment funds of, first, Florida, and, then, North Carolina without complaint.

So when the Salisbury Post eliminated my position as managing editor in late November, I expected the state to help me and many others who have lost their jobs get through this difficult time.

I have found the state's system needlessly confusing and all but impossible to navigate. The state has provided no system of instructions that helps someone like me get through the bureaucratic morass, and employees of the local Unemployment Security Commission office have failed to provide key pieces of information. If I had not found out through other unemployed people, I would not have corrected the latest error in filing. And so far, I have yet to receive a single check.

Quite honestly, I find the system that is supposed to help me and others actually leaves puts the burden on us to unravel the many rules on our own. And I thought you and the board you serve as well as my local legislators should know it.

First, let me say I am one of the lucky ones because I have a seven-month severance package, and my wife still has a good job. So I have not suffered while I looked for a new job and tried to learn the many complex and conflicting unemployment rules. But I'm sure many others do not have that same support, and making it tough on them is not right. Plus, besides tuition and books for a class at RCCC, I'm also paying $6,000 in advance for only a six-month paralegal certificate program at the University of North Carolina at Charlotte, and my wife and I are struggling to get help for our disabled daughter.

Here's a summary of what I have encountered:

On the advice of others who had lost jobs, I registered for unemployment on Nov. 30, 2008. At the time, I went to the Salisbury center on South Main and told the counselor I had already enrolled at Rowan-Cabarrus Community College and planned to take courses in January. He said I only needed to return with my schedule and enrollment papers, which I did in January, and that I could get benefits even though I was also getting my severance. I believe this is a very common practice and helps people cover the cost of going back to school.

When the benefits didn't start, I went online and learned that my case had been declared inactive and I would have to reapply in person at the Unemployment office. Maybe I'm denser than others, but no one told me I need to file the weekly certification report in addition to providing proof of my enrollment.

Also at that time, the counselor told me that the office had received papers from my former company which someone else had to read to me before my benefits could proceed. The person in question was out of the office and no one else could fine the papers. The counselor would or could not tell me the nature of the "papers."

The following week, I returned to the office and was directed to a manager who said the Post management had challenged my right to benefits, saying I left voluntarily. Had I known the nature of the "papers," I could have come to the office prepared with a copy of an e-mail saying my position had been eliminated.

Remember also that your office never contacted me about this challenge. If I hadn't gone in to reactivate my file, I might still not know.

I had to get documentation and make another trip to the office, where I also wrote a statement of my position on my job loss. The manager warned me that the "determination" in Raleigh could take months. That -- I'm pleased to say -- was also wrong. In two weeks, I got a letter saying my benefits had been approved.

 By this time, I am in my fourth week of school, and I expected to receive a check immediately. Then, earlier this week, another person who lost his job and was enrolled at RCCC  said he was not getting his benefits yet. When he went to the Unemployment Office, a counselor told him that despite the explicit language on the weekly certification questionnaire, he was not supposed to acknowledge receiving severance pay.

Keep in mind that the online report form warns you, first, that any false statement can be prosecuted as a felony. And the report then explicitly asks if you are receiving severance pay -- not mentioning any waiver for taking classes. Neither my friend nor I was told to essentially lie about receiving severance on the weekly report.

I called the Salsibury Unemployment Office today and a manager confirmed that I had not been receiving checks because I was reporting the severance. He said that your records show I have a waiver for enrolling at RCCC and I should not report my severance pay. Now that I had called, the manager said he would go back and change the records so that I will get two checks in arrears. Quite honestly, he seemed put out that I didn't know I was supposed to answer the weekly report incorrectly.

I was so astonished by the latest twist that I immediately sat down and wrote this e-mail. As I said previously, I might be dense because I have been lucky enough never to file for unemployment before and don't "know the system." But I consider myself an average, loyal taxpayer and citizen of North Carolina, and I think your system is horrendous.

Sincerely,

