RALEIGH The long-running Leandro schools suit -- first filed in 1995 and still overseen by Wake Superior Court Judge Howard Manning --
is all about whether the state is fulfilling its constitutional duty to give every child the opportunity to receive a sound basic education.
It involves resources, teachers and principals and whether schools deliver on their promise.

But in a state that condones a public schools governance system that deliberately misleads the public and students, confuses taxpayers and
contributes to a dysfunctional administrative structure, it's a wonder schools perform as well as they do. Consider:

The Constitution requires statewide election of a Superintendent of Public Instruction every four years. The implicit promise is that this
superintendent will run the state's schools and be accountable to voters every general election. But it's a farce. The superintendent has
no power to do anything, and when voters wonder why their elected education official can't make schools perform better, they might
as well be wondering whether thunder curdles milk. It's a meaningless exercise.

*An empty position*

* *

**The Constitution also creates an appointed State Board of Education, and gives it oversight of public schools and the authority to delegate
power to operate the schools. In the past, the board has sometimes given that power to the Superintendent of Public Instruction -- such
as former Superintendents Craig Phillips and Mike Ward, who had the board's confidence. In others, the board has withheld that authority,
such as with former Superintendent Bobby Etheridge, now a member of Congress, and June Atkinson, the current superintendent.

This hydra-headed structure means that everyone is in charge and no one is in charge. Governors like to run on a ticket of becoming
education governors, and they appoint most of the members of the board. But the board often hires its own de facto schools superintendent
to run daily operations. It's no wonder that a consulting firm's study of our system labels it "dysfunctional." That's education jargon for
"a train wreck."

"From the perspective of thoughtful and consistent public policy, this shifting every few years of authority and roles has been confusing,
inconsistent and largely politically driven," asserts the report by Evergreen Solutions.

That study also noted that stakeholders in the education system thought the governance structure "is broken in North Carolina. It is an
impossible arrangement set up for failure and confusion" because no one knows where to go to get a consistent answer about schools policy.

*Logically bankrupt system*

* *

**A few weeks ago, Gov. Bev Perdue attempted to resolve some of the confusion over this logically bankrupt system of governance.
She announced that longtime State Board of Education Chairman Howard Lee will step down to take another education post; that
she will appoint Cumberland County Schools Superintendent Bill Harrison to the board, and that she wants the board to name
Harrison its new chairman and to make him the chief executive officer of N.C. public schools.

She did this with the state's university and community college leaders, as well as Superintendent of Public Instruction June Atkinson,
standing with her on a podium. Atkinson, the governor said, would continue as an ambassador to public schools and work on other
issues. Is there a more awkward post in government?

Perdue said she did not want to wait for the 18 months or two years it might take to change the Constitution to resolve the governance
issue. The state's schools and its students need clarity in policymaking now, and she is absolutely right.

But in avoiding a debate over whether to change the Constitution to either make clear that the superintendent is in charge, or perhaps
to abolish the job of superintendent, the governor is doing the same thing that the General Assembly has done for decades: ignoring a
mess that everyone knows cheats the public about who's in charge and deprives students of the best schools system the state could
give them.

Now the N.C. Public Schools Forum, an education think tank, has completed a study calling for a constitutional amendment eliminating
the elected superintendent's position and giving the State Board of Education authority to hire a Commissioner of K-12 Education.
It also recommended giving some appointments to the state board to the leaders of the state House and Senate. It's a good idea. If the
legislature wanted to take just one step to reassure the public about accountability for schools, this is it.

*Whose job is it?*

* *

**As former state Sen. Gerry Hancock, a Public School Forum board member, put it, "Whose job is it to solve the intractable problems
that affect our children?"

*Resistance to education governance change has always boiled down to politics.* The legislature doesn't want to be perceived
as taking a vote away from voters. But in sticking with that Jacksonian notion, it is complicit in a governance structure where no one
is really in charge -- and *where children are the ones who pay the price.*

*Correction:* In last week's column about school desegregation in Virginia and North Carolina, I named the wrong county that once
closed its doors rather than opening white schools to black students. It was Prince Edward County, southwest of Richmond, and
not Prince William County, near the Washington, D.C. suburbs.


